WEBVTT

00:01.218 --> 00:05.646
Well, thank you so much for being out with us on this Wednesday night for Lent.

00:06.547 --> 00:09.913
It's an interesting season for us as Christ followers, isn't it?

00:09.933 --> 00:17.946
I have to tell you that preparing for this evening proved to be a little bit more difficult than I had kind of thought that it originally would be.

00:18.608 --> 00:25.720
And my coworkers would joke that that's because I'm not supposed to speak for very long, which is truly part of the challenge for me.

00:25.740 --> 00:27.122
But I promise you, I'm going to keep it

00:27.490 --> 00:28.551
on point this evening.

00:28.971 --> 00:39.622
But the truth of the matter is that as Christ followers, we just know God has called us to go into all the world and share the good news of Jesus, the hope that he is.

00:39.682 --> 00:55.538
So when we have these opportunities to gather together into publicly proclaim, I can speak, a message, it is of course just the most natural thing to wanna just navigate into those spaces of the good news, the hope of Jesus.

00:55.618 --> 01:00.806
So I find myself in this tug of war as we kind of approach this season of Lent.

01:01.386 --> 01:04.070
And I would guess that many of you might feel that same way.

01:04.090 --> 01:20.274
We're kind of caught in that middle between that place of like knowing what is absolutely true about the hope of Jesus and this season where we're asked to just pause and intentionally focus on those parts of us that

01:20.386 --> 01:28.658
are weak or lacking or really demonstrate this profound need that we have of an incredible God.

01:28.802 --> 01:34.668
And so it's kind of been in that struggle that I started to discover truly the beauty of this season.

01:35.208 --> 01:41.834
And I hope that the fact that you're here is demonstrating that you're discovering some of that for yourselves as well.

01:42.415 --> 01:58.130
Because what I've come to find out that it's in this place where we start to discover some of those things about ourselves that make us so desperate for a big God in our lives, that we also begin to grow a bigger concept of who our God is.

01:58.690 --> 02:01.234
So let me ask you this question tonight.

02:02.255 --> 02:04.719
How big is your God?

02:04.759 --> 02:08.806
Now I'm not suggesting for a moment that we each have a different God.

02:08.846 --> 02:11.309
Gotta make sure I'm not like speaking heresy up here.

02:11.370 --> 02:12.792
Anything Pastor Mark would not be pleased.

02:12.812 --> 02:16.497
So I'm not suggesting that we each have a different God.

02:16.517 --> 02:19.021
There is only one true God.

02:19.041 --> 02:24.690
But our perception of God matters tremendously.

02:24.710 --> 02:27.314
So let me ask you again,

02:27.554 --> 02:30.840
How big is your God?

02:30.901 --> 02:35.329
Because your answer to that question will reflect two things.

02:35.970 --> 02:37.153
And the first one is this.

02:37.213 --> 02:42.643
It will reflect how big the things are that you're willing to trust God with.

02:42.684 --> 02:50.098
And secondly, it will reflect what you believe at your very core about your own humanity.

02:51.266 --> 02:56.975
Now I want to spend most of our time tonight talking about that second point because that really is the spirit of Lent.

02:56.995 --> 03:03.826
It's going to help us understand the first point and about hopefully help shift our perspective about how big our God is.

03:04.247 --> 03:07.132
But I do want to just say this quickly about that first point.

03:08.374 --> 03:18.610
The past couple of weeks here at the church, there have been at least two different people who have come in for prayer because they found out in the last couple of weeks that they've had a diagnosis of cancer.

03:19.074 --> 03:28.907
And I want you to note, these are unrelated people to each other, but both of them have without a doubt a very big view of God.

03:28.947 --> 03:34.675
And here's how I've seen it played out in their lives as they come in and they've been sharing our journey with us.

03:35.376 --> 03:36.217
The first is this.

03:36.718 --> 03:45.490
In each of their cases, they without a doubt know that their God orchestrated the events that led them to this diagnosis.

03:45.922 --> 03:52.731
Now, you see, when we have a small view of God, then we tend to look at that time and we think, oh, how could this happen to me?

03:52.751 --> 03:53.813
How could God allow this?

03:53.833 --> 03:57.778
How could I be in this place where suddenly I'm struggling with this awful disease?

03:58.118 --> 04:02.064
But when we have a big view of God, that's where we can start to see.

04:02.084 --> 04:12.658
And I'm telling you, both of these people saw so clearly, and we're just so grateful for how God had orchestrated those things that led them to the place of finding out what was not right within them.

04:13.634 --> 04:23.468
And there's a spiritual lesson for us to learn there because in this season of Lent, it is about this season of figuring out what within us is not exactly quite right.

04:24.409 --> 04:36.466
And I hope you know that your God, if you've got a big view of God and hopefully it's just going to keep growing, he's been orchestrating things and putting things in place that we can discover those things that maybe aren't quite right within us.

04:37.122 --> 04:47.397
The other thing that has really set these people apart that just showed me, gosh, they really do have a big view of God, is they know without a doubt that God has orchestrated the medical team who is coming around them.

04:47.758 --> 04:50.882
And in one of the cases, I kid you not, she told me the story.

04:50.942 --> 05:00.596
God has been clearly orchestrating it for almost 20 years to bring this person to the point to be part of this medical team right now in this moment.

05:01.498 --> 05:04.562
That is a big view of God.

05:05.058 --> 05:09.906
And in both of these cases, I want you to know healing is not even a question.

05:09.966 --> 05:13.352
They know that their God is going to bring them healing.

05:13.372 --> 05:20.283
And it might be supernaturally, it might be through the medicine, and it might be by bringing them to heaven.

05:20.404 --> 05:23.669
But gosh, by golly, they are going to get their healing.

05:23.709 --> 05:27.475
That is a big view of God.

05:27.495 --> 05:29.138
Yeah, you can praise that.

05:30.370 --> 05:50.650
And those are the things that's what this season is intended to help us with, to start to understand some of those things within us that aren't quite right, that make us in some sense desperate for a bigger God than maybe the one that we've somehow constructed in our own thinking by keeping him too small and not opening up all the spaces of our life to him.

05:51.451 --> 05:54.654
So I want you to know there's a verse that I want to share with you because it's so beautiful.

05:54.734 --> 05:55.555
It's in the Psalms.

05:55.575 --> 05:58.258
There's just a lot of great things in the Psalms.

05:58.434 --> 06:04.586
choosing this one verse to share with you, but it is truly a verse that speaks to the heart of somebody who has a big view of God.

06:04.646 --> 06:11.419
It's written in the 112th Psalm, and it says this, that person, he is not afraid of bad news.

06:12.160 --> 06:15.186
His heart is firm, trusting in the Lord.

06:16.258 --> 06:17.801
That's the kind of heart that I wanna have.

06:17.821 --> 06:31.383
That's the kind of heart that God is hopefully cultivating in us as we continue to go before him and allow him to keep expanding our view, expanding our understanding of how great and how big and how holy he truly is.

06:32.284 --> 06:43.282
So you see, it's in that process now that we're gonna get to that second point because I told you our view of God and how big he is, it will determine how big the things are that we'll trust him with, but it will also reflect

06:43.618 --> 06:46.344
at our core what we believe about our humanity.

06:46.364 --> 06:49.530
And this is really the stuff of Lent.

06:50.372 --> 06:56.424
Now, if you were with us last week, Pastor Phil talked about the practice of fasting, of giving something up.

06:56.444 --> 07:01.395
And I might get this analogy a little bit wrong, but I think I have it generally on track.

07:01.415 --> 07:03.058
So, Pastor Phil, please forgive me if I'm not.

07:03.362 --> 07:13.459
But he had talked about the fact that when we navigate into these spaces, when we give things up, it kind of sends us into unchartered grounds because we're so used to our comforts, right?

07:13.479 --> 07:18.107
We're not so accustomed to telling ourselves no and practicing that self-denial kind of thing.

07:18.127 --> 07:20.050
And he gave the example of

07:20.450 --> 07:30.530
Back in the day, so a long time ago, when they used to draw out charts or maps of land, you know, there was only this perspective that lasted as far as what any of them had ever seen.

07:30.631 --> 07:33.937
So, for example, a map person was going to draw out a map of a kingdom.

07:33.997 --> 07:36.001
They could only draw as far as they understood.

07:36.102 --> 07:37.444
So there would be some natural boundaries.

07:37.885 --> 07:42.194
And they considered that land beyond that the place where the dragons lived.

07:42.658 --> 07:45.401
because it was that place of mystery and the unknown.

07:45.441 --> 07:55.270
And you didn't know when you got there if you were gonna encounter something that was scary and difficult, or if you might encounter something that would be wonderful and good as well.

07:55.290 --> 07:57.392
And they referred to it as the place that the dragons live.

07:57.412 --> 08:11.346
And it is in that place so often when we encounter the unexpected that God begins to show us some things in ourself that maybe need to be dealt with, that maybe aren't quite right, that needed to be diagnosed in our life.

08:11.874 --> 08:33.047
But tonight I wanna shift our focus actually back to the land where we always live because there is something very real in our very present experience that also if we pay attention to it has such power to show us also that great need that we have of a holy God and it is that land of disappointment.

08:34.389 --> 08:35.170
We've all been there.

08:35.971 --> 08:40.338
I would guess chances are today that each of us has experienced some degree of disappointment.

08:40.834 --> 08:43.218
And I'm not even talking about a disappointment with others.

08:43.899 --> 08:47.044
I'm talking about that disappointment that comes with ourselves.

08:48.467 --> 08:51.872
You know, disappointment comes in lots of shapes and sizes.

08:52.734 --> 08:56.460
Often we can be disappointed about things that we've done or things that we haven't done.

08:56.520 --> 08:59.905
Disappointments can also be rather trivial.

09:00.446 --> 09:05.234
We might be disappointed that maybe God didn't give us an ability to be

09:05.314 --> 09:08.198
Well, for me, I wish I was a little more mechanically inclined.

09:08.399 --> 09:12.826
I think it'd be really great to, in some that I could have learned, but I'm not real mechanically inclined.

09:13.126 --> 09:18.815
We might be disappointed that maybe he didn't give us a better metabolism, and we have to work a little harder at keeping ourselves healthy.

09:18.835 --> 09:24.263
We might be disappointed that we don't have a certain gift for making things beautiful or nice or pretty.

09:24.303 --> 09:31.154
And in the grand scope of things, we understand those are all just kind of trivial things, but they create some disappointment in our lives.

09:31.522 --> 09:38.530
But some disappointments are also quite honestly, forgive the word, I hope it doesn't offend you, but some of them are just neurotic.

09:39.552 --> 09:42.635
And what I mean by that is they are so outside of our control.

09:42.696 --> 09:48.282
They are the disappointments that we take on ourselves based on absolutely nothing that is truthful.

09:48.322 --> 10:01.298
They're the disappointments that we experience when we're navigating into a place of people we don't know and we suddenly find ourselves worried about what everybody is thinking and what they're saying and what they must think of us.

10:01.986 --> 10:04.368
And the truth of the matter is, we all know this.

10:05.069 --> 10:08.432
Chances are nobody's paying attention to you as much as you're paying attention to you.

10:08.492 --> 10:13.037
So they tend to be in that place that we don't even have control.

10:13.097 --> 10:25.309
Some of the disappointments that we experience are really the fruit of this day and age where we are so self-absorbed, so self-focused.

10:25.329 --> 10:30.674
Those kinds of disappointments eke their little heads when we go to places like our high school reunions.

10:31.490 --> 10:34.874
and we wish that maybe we looked a little better, had lost a little more weight.

10:35.615 --> 10:39.920
We maybe wish that we had achieved a little bit more because we believe that we might look better.

10:39.940 --> 10:44.204
Others might esteem us in some way and we feel a little disappointed with ourselves.

10:45.226 --> 10:59.762
The disappointments that happen if maybe you're in a situation where you're still pursuing that guy or that girl you've had your eye on for some time and you find yourself surrounded by them and you wanna just say like the most engaging thing to get in a conversation and at best it came out as ordinary.

10:59.906 --> 11:04.253
And at worst, what you really believe is it was awkward and clumsy.

11:04.293 --> 11:11.764
And we're disappointed because we didn't quite do it the way that we had really hoped in some way, shape or form.

11:12.906 --> 11:16.291
But there are also some disappointments that run much deeper.

11:16.331 --> 11:19.756
And these are the ones that we really want to get to the heart of tonight.

11:20.657 --> 11:21.899
These are the kind of disappointments.

11:21.959 --> 11:29.170
If you're a parent in the room tonight, I'm sure you've had this moment where you stood at the door of your child's room as they were sleeping at night.

11:29.474 --> 11:35.381
and you've looked in and you thought to yourself, I didn't do it right today.

11:35.401 --> 11:40.907
I definitely gave more time and attention to my phone than to my child.

11:42.168 --> 11:49.717
Or maybe you know that you definitely lost it on your kids when all they really did was be kids.

11:51.980 --> 11:57.586
You know, we grow so disappointed with ourselves and those arenas of being parents or spouses

11:57.922 --> 12:12.596
or children of adult parents, we can be disappointed with how we are as friends or neighbors or as followers of Jesus, where we know that there's no greater mission put before us than to tell people about the hope of the world.

12:13.457 --> 12:19.262
But we seem to struggle to ever get his name off our lips when we're talking to people who don't know him.

12:20.363 --> 12:23.586
And it just breeds more disappointment in ourselves.

12:25.108 --> 12:27.570
So it really does beg the question where

12:27.714 --> 12:29.817
does this disappointment come from?

12:29.857 --> 12:36.308
Because I think we would all agree it's just part of our reality, regardless of how long you have been following the Lord.

12:36.348 --> 12:40.574
I'm gonna tell you you struggle, we all struggle with this area of disappointment.

12:41.676 --> 12:50.710
Now the common answer to where this came from is that of course it's just that it can be an issue of self-esteem or a failure to accept some part of yourself and that might be part of it.

12:50.750 --> 12:55.538
I think there's definitely some truth in those kinds of things, but it's definitely not the whole picture.

12:56.322 --> 13:05.656
In the older we get, the wiser we get, we will start to discover that disappointment is not actually the problem.

13:05.716 --> 13:12.006
That feeling of disappointment, we wanna deal with that, but the feeling of disappointment is really not the problem.

13:12.346 --> 13:22.602
What it is, is it's a reflection of the actual problem, which is our failure to be the person that God had in mind when He created us.

13:24.124 --> 13:25.266
This disappointment.

13:25.858 --> 13:36.414
is where that ache comes from in our heart, those deeper places of disappointment in our lives, knowing wholeheartedly that God must have had something else in mind when he created us.

13:38.356 --> 13:47.210
Do you remember, this might seem a little off track, but it's gonna make sense in a second, do you wanna remember the cartoon days of Popeye the Sailor Man?

13:47.991 --> 13:52.978
I'm gonna show my age here real quick, because some of you don't even know him, but good old Popeye, Popeye the Sailor Man.

13:53.442 --> 13:55.365
I'm strong to the finish, because I eat my spinach.

13:55.385 --> 13:56.587
I'm Popeye the Sailor Man.

13:56.947 --> 13:57.368
Remember that one?

13:57.508 --> 13:57.969
Yeah.

13:58.209 --> 13:58.970
I love Popeye.

13:59.070 --> 14:03.116
I was a kid who grew up on this Saturday morning cartoons in the 70s and 80s.

14:03.517 --> 14:10.507
And there was something about Popeye that I think speaks strangely enough to this condition of our hearts and our souls, this disappointment that's within us.

14:11.048 --> 14:13.973
Because if you remember, Popeye had a few like sayings.

14:14.073 --> 14:15.675
Actually, he had some good sayings.

14:16.016 --> 14:20.242
But there was one that I think always just stuck with me over time, and it is this.

14:20.322 --> 14:27.259
Pop I would say whenever he would kind of find himself in a jam or not quite doing what he's supposed to do, he would always say, well, I am what I am.

14:27.320 --> 14:28.843
Remember that one?

14:28.863 --> 14:31.249
That was his thing.

14:31.610 --> 14:37.906
And in essence when he was saying that it was, there was kind of this tone to it that unfortunately felt a little bit sad to me.

14:38.242 --> 14:46.931
Because usually when he would say it, it was kind of in that space of saying, well, I just need to kind of explain why I've fallen short here, why I haven't quite come up with it.

14:46.951 --> 14:48.753
You know, I am what I am.

14:48.773 --> 14:50.555
I don't expect too much from me.

14:50.575 --> 14:55.180
It seemed to say that, and actually he would take it a step further when things were really bad.

14:55.200 --> 14:57.243
He would say, I am what I am.

14:57.263 --> 15:00.606
And then he'd say, and that's all that I am.

15:00.646 --> 15:04.230
And I feel like that's the cry of us as humans.

15:04.691 --> 15:07.794
Sometimes we sit back and we look at these disappointments and we think,

15:07.906 --> 15:10.408
Well, I am what I am.

15:10.448 --> 15:12.470
What can I do about it?

15:13.912 --> 15:18.857
And I want you to know that that's the space that God wants us to be paying attention to.

15:18.897 --> 15:23.281
That's why the church goes through seasons where they say, let's focus in.

15:23.341 --> 15:29.888
Let's pay attention to that because there's something in that that speaks to the human existence.

15:30.648 --> 15:36.434
Now there's, I wanna tell you another quick story and then I'll bring this around and actually we'll be wrapping it up fairly quickly.

15:36.578 --> 15:39.543
There was this incredible work of art that Michelangelo did years ago.

15:39.563 --> 15:43.950
It was a marble statue of Mary holding the crucified Christ.

15:44.972 --> 15:45.633
And I might not remember.

15:45.673 --> 15:46.875
I think it was in the Vatican.

15:47.256 --> 15:48.918
I don't know that actually for a fact.

15:49.700 --> 15:51.322
But I believe it was housed in the Vatican.

15:51.403 --> 15:55.049
And some years ago, there was somebody who came into the Vatican.

15:55.349 --> 16:03.122
I don't know how they got in there, but they got in with a sledgehammer and they literally took this masterpiece and they smashed it to pieces.

16:04.194 --> 16:12.665
Well, the artists at the vat, I think it was the Vatican, they went to work and they were able to restore this incredible masterpiece almost to near perfect condition.

16:13.987 --> 16:16.670
And I was thinking about that masterpiece and I thought, you know what?

16:17.491 --> 16:22.778
I don't know if you know this, but God has made each one of us to be a masterpiece as well.

16:23.579 --> 16:31.730
It actually tells us in the book of Ephesians, chapter two, it says this, we are God's workmanship, created in Christ Jesus for good works.

16:31.906 --> 16:34.729
which God prepared beforehand that we should walk in them.

16:34.769 --> 16:47.041
Now the word workmanship in this verse, the Greek word is Puyema, that doesn't really matter, but it's a word that means God's work of art.

16:48.542 --> 16:54.648
Each one of us, we were designed as God's masterpiece, his work of art.

16:55.389 --> 17:00.914
We were meant to reflect his image in this world and to be in relationship with us.

17:01.218 --> 17:07.407
And you see, the fallen world has brought the sledgehammer down on that image at work inside of each of us.

17:08.228 --> 17:17.642
So that disappointment that we experience, that deeper disappointment, it is actually a reflection of why it runs so deep.

17:18.563 --> 17:23.830
And it is because that very image has somehow been destroyed in each and every one of us.

17:25.132 --> 17:26.194
But here's the good news.

17:27.295 --> 17:29.138
God is super diligent.

17:29.602 --> 17:35.568
and he really has been going to work to restore the masterpiece that he intended each one of us to be.

17:35.608 --> 17:38.712
But you see, we have to go through this process.

17:38.752 --> 17:43.978
We have to figure out what do we do with that disappointment because it is meant to be a reflection of something.

17:44.018 --> 17:46.680
It is meant to be able to drive us toward action.

17:46.740 --> 17:55.570
This season of Lent is meant for us to reflect in these things so that we can come to a greater understanding of why it is that we so desperately need a big God

17:56.162 --> 17:59.646
So in those places, I think it's worth us asking a few questions.

18:00.147 --> 18:01.108
The first one is this.

18:01.748 --> 18:10.919
As we go our way this week, I just am gonna encourage you, I want you to spend some time just thinking about and identifying those disappointments that you carry in yourself.

18:12.341 --> 18:20.530
Now this is where we have to be careful because if you are not already a believer in Jesus, the enemy will use it to bring condemnation on you.

18:21.602 --> 18:34.988
He will tell you that because of these things, because of these disappointments, you are not worthy, you are not good, you just, there's nothing of value in you, and that is a lie from the pit of hell that comes straight from the devil's mouth, okay?

18:35.870 --> 18:42.002
So when I tell you that it's important for us to identify our disappointments, we need to do it through the lens of a Christ follower.

18:42.530 --> 18:45.212
And so if that's not you, I'm going to encourage you this evening too.

18:45.413 --> 18:49.036
As before you do this examination, you have to just trust Jesus.

18:49.076 --> 18:56.242
You need to say to him first, I'm going to trust you to be the Lord of this because this is meant to be a good process for us, a healthy process for us.

18:56.802 --> 19:08.853
So when we can go through and we can start to identify those things, those areas in our life that are disappointments, they are the very areas that more than likely are the spaces where we're not lining up with the image that God created us to be.

19:08.913 --> 19:12.516
That word disappointment, I think it's such a perfect

19:12.496 --> 19:16.384
word because it implies a diss of appointment.

19:16.745 --> 19:19.772
We are missing what we have been appointed by God to be.

19:19.852 --> 19:22.879
You see, God called us to something greater.

19:22.919 --> 19:24.442
He called us to reflect His image.

19:24.462 --> 19:26.406
He called us to be in relationship with Him.

19:26.947 --> 19:30.034
All of these things are gifts to us as followers of His.

19:30.466 --> 19:44.822
But they require us to navigate through these spaces of sometimes the not feeling so good so that we can truly embrace and continue to grow our picture of who he is and walk into an even deeper place of relationship with him.

19:46.084 --> 19:47.886
God forbid we ever think we've arrived.

19:48.927 --> 19:51.069
God forbid we ever think we've got him figured out.

19:51.990 --> 19:53.892
You know, that is the greatest thing about this journey.

19:53.932 --> 19:58.898
We have to continue to keep ourselves open and God will continue to reveal some great new truth to us.

19:59.170 --> 20:01.252
So again, that's step one, identify it.

20:01.753 --> 20:05.097
Spend some time asking God, where are those great disappointments of my life, Lord?

20:05.477 --> 20:09.942
Because chances are they are a reflection of those areas that maybe haven't been aligning with His image.

20:10.623 --> 20:16.029
Number two, once you've figured it out, once you've identified it, you need to look for the wisdom in it.

20:17.290 --> 20:27.602
I told you about these families who could look at the fact that they received a diagnosis and see so clearly that God had His hand in it by how He orchestrated the events leading up to their diagnosis.

20:28.034 --> 20:35.126
We have to look for the wisdom in the space that he has made us aware of these areas that we aren't quite meeting the mark.

20:35.627 --> 20:38.592
These places in our lives where we're not quite reaching his standard.

20:39.374 --> 20:47.989
Ask yourself if there's something that triggers you in this area, if there's a pattern that you might identify that brings you to that space.

20:48.610 --> 20:51.154
So then you can look for the grace to help you with it.

20:51.938 --> 21:00.547
And then lastly, once we've identified it, once we've asked for some wisdom in it because we are gonna trust that God is good in bringing these things to our attention.

21:00.567 --> 21:03.591
The only way we get healing is by God's grace, right?

21:03.631 --> 21:06.174
And having understanding of what that thing is in our lives.

21:06.634 --> 21:09.657
But then number three, we have to invite the great I am into it.

21:10.839 --> 21:21.330
When Moses was in the desert and God first told him that he needed to go back to Egypt and release the Israelites from bondage there, he was so full of doubt and disappointment in his life.

21:21.794 --> 21:24.137
And he even questioned God and said, but what if?

21:24.177 --> 21:24.617
What if?

21:24.658 --> 21:25.939
What if he was filled with what if?

21:26.500 --> 21:34.990
And his last question was, well, what if they asked me who you are, who the God is that sent me and God said, then you tell them, I am that I am.

21:35.010 --> 21:38.114
And it was the great I am that sent him.

21:38.154 --> 21:43.020
So my friends, when we get into those places of, well, I am what I am.

21:43.040 --> 21:45.503
And that's all that I am.

21:45.563 --> 21:50.930
That's the space where we invite the great I am.

21:51.362 --> 21:59.434
because a big God in our small weaknesses and our small failings and our small shortcomings can do a mighty, mighty work.

22:00.175 --> 22:01.738
But we have to invite him in.

22:02.278 --> 22:03.761
We have to be part of the process.

22:04.201 --> 22:09.249
Just like Pop, I had to open up his cans of spinach so he could be strong and he had to eat it down in his own.

22:09.289 --> 22:12.213
He knew it was weak, but he had to do that process.

22:12.293 --> 22:17.201
So too, we have to be active in it and invite the great I am to come into those spaces.

22:18.182 --> 22:20.626
Remember, God is determined

22:21.186 --> 22:24.389
to overcome the defacing of His image in each of us.

22:25.390 --> 22:26.952
You are His workmanship.

22:27.593 --> 22:29.575
You are His work of art.

22:30.576 --> 22:46.833
And we have to embrace the opportunity that we have when we see these places in our lives that just don't align with that image reflecting in us and seek Him to continue to help us to grow in those places and just make more and more room for Him so we can better reflect His image.

22:47.253 --> 22:47.794
Amen.

22:48.962 --> 22:51.709
So I'm going to ask you this evening as you go out to the tables.

22:51.849 --> 22:54.616
I know that this area of disappointment, it's a vulnerable place.

22:54.636 --> 22:57.623
So I'm not going to ask you to go out and start sharing all your disappointments with each other.

22:57.643 --> 22:59.548
None of you would come back.

22:59.568 --> 23:02.194
You'd be like, I'm not doing this length thing anymore.

23:02.722 --> 23:07.911
But by all means, if you're with a group of people on your table that you do know and you navigate in those conversations, that's great.

23:07.971 --> 23:08.793
Praise the Lord for it.

23:08.953 --> 23:11.297
Be willing to be vulnerable with some people in your lives.

23:11.337 --> 23:12.379
That is really important.

23:12.740 --> 23:17.608
But I get that most of us will be sitting with groups of people that we don't necessarily know with that kind of safety and comfort.

23:18.069 --> 23:23.859
But I would encourage you as you're spending that time tonight as we go out and we start to grab our soup and have some time to fellowship out there.

23:24.220 --> 23:27.826
By all means, at least take this step and introduce yourselves to each other.

23:27.906 --> 23:46.425
But then I think it would also be just a great question or if you maybe have your own story of some time when you learned something, it could be a diagnosis, it could be where God just showed you something that was a weakness in your life that you can now identify and hold on to and share as a story of God's goodness through that.

23:46.445 --> 23:49.368
If you have one of those stories, would you do me a favor?

23:49.408 --> 23:54.834
When you're sitting at your table tonight, can you just take the bold step, take the awkward step,

23:55.106 --> 23:58.072
We're all, can everybody say, I agree, it'll be okay if somebody's awkward at my table.

23:58.153 --> 23:59.275
God bless them.

24:00.077 --> 24:04.146
But take that awkward step and just say, hey, I've got a story and share it with us.

24:04.206 --> 24:08.074
Let's be encouraged by the way God has been showing up and moving in the lives of each other, okay?

24:08.836 --> 24:09.056
Okay.

24:09.999 --> 24:13.426
So just a reminder, our youth program is going until eight o'clock.

24:13.506 --> 24:36.086
So I'm gonna ask you to, I know last week we had navigated down there, you were so gracious to wait for them, but what we failed to tell you is that at the end of youth, they always break into small groups, and some of the small groups meet out in that little lobby area, so I really would ask you if you have students who are down in the area, can you just make sure that you wait to even enter the area until eight o'clock, because there's some groups that will be going on in that time.

24:36.686 --> 24:43.492
If you have kids, however, in preschool or down in the grade school area, you can pick them up before you go out, but then otherwise,

24:43.472 --> 24:48.645
soup is ready, so we invite you to go out, grab some soup, find a table, find some people, and spend some time with each other.

24:48.685 --> 24:51.733
And thank you so much for coming out and spending tonight with us.

24:51.773 --> 24:52.595
God bless all of you guys.

24:52.635 --> 24:53.938
We'll see you on Sunday.

